===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|abaten|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|abatre||to beat down|lang=fro}} (possibly via {{etyl|frm|en}}), from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|abbatto|lang=la}}, from {{term|ab-|lang=la||away}} + {{term|batto||lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|battuere||lang=la|to beat}}. Cognate to modern French ''[[abattre]]''.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|abat}}

# {{context|transitive|obsolete|outside|legal|lang=en}} To put an end to; to cause to cease. {{defdate|attested since about 1150 to 1350}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''to '''abate''' a nuisance''
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To become null and void. {{defdate|attested since the late 15th century}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''The writ has '''abated'''.''
# {{context|transitive|legal|lang=en}} To [[nullify]]; make void. {{defdate|attested since the late 15th century}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''to '''abate''' a writ''
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[humble]]; to lower in status; to bring someone down physically or mentally. {{defdate|attested from around 1150 to 1350 until the mid 1600s}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* [[w:Geoffrey Chaucer|Geoffrey Chaucer]]
#*: ''The hyer that they were in this present lyf, the moore shulle they be '''abated''' and defouled in helle.''
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To be humbled; to be brought down physically or mentally. {{defdate|attested from around 1150 to 1350 until the mid 1600s}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To curtail; to deprive. {{defdate|attested from around 1350 to 1470 until the mid 1800s}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''Order restrictions and prohibitions to '''abate''' an emergency situation.''
#* '''1605''', [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''King Lear'', II.ii:
#*: ''She hath '''abated''' me of half my train.''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[reduce]] in amount, size, or value. {{defdate|attested since 1325}}<ref name = Chambers>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref><ref name=SOED/>
#: ''Legacies are liable to be '''abated''' entirely or in proportion, upon a deficiency of assets.''
#* {{RQ:Authorized Version|Deuteronomy|34|7}}
#*: His eye was not dim, nor his natural force '''abated'''.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To decrease in size, value, or amount. {{defdate|attested since 1325}}<ref name = Chambers/>
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[moderate]]; to lessen in force, [[intensity]], to [[subside]]. {{defdate|attested since around 1150 to 1350}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''1597''', [[w:Francis Bacon|Francis Bacon]], ''[http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/575 Essays or Counsels, Civil and Morall]'':
#*: Not that they feel it so, but only to '''abate''' the edge of envy.
#* '''1855''', [[w:Thomas Babington Macaulay|Thomas Babington Macaulay]], ''History of England from the Accession of James II, Part 3'', [http://books.google.com/books?id=MN5CNdgbSTYC&pg=PA267 page 267]:
#*: The fury of Glengarry{{...|, not being inflamed by any fresh provocation,}} rapidly '''abated'''.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To decrease in intensity or force; to subside. {{defdate|attested since around 1150 to 1350}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{circa|1719}} [[w:Daniel Defoe|Daniel Defoe]], ''[[w:Robinson Crusoe|Robinson Crusoe]]'':
#*: {{...}} in the morning, the wind having '''abated''' overnight, the sea was calm, {{...}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[deduct]] or [[omit]]. {{defdate|attested since around 1350 to 1470}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''We will '''abate''' this price from the total.''
#* '''1845''', [[w:Thomas Fuller|Thomas Fuller]], ''The Church History of Britain'', Volume 3, [http://books.google.com/books?id=OfefAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA100 page 100]:
#*: Allowing nine thousand parishes ('''abating''' the odd hundreds) in England and Wales {{...}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[bar]] or [[except]]. {{defdate|attested since the late 1500s}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* [[w:Samuel Johnson|Samuel Johnson]]
#*: '''''Abating''' his brutality, he was a very good master.''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To cut away or hammer down, in such a way as to leave a figure in relief, as a sculpture, or in metalwork.
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To dull the edge or point of; to [[blunt]]. {{defdate|attested from the mid 1500s till the late 1600s}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|transitive|archaic|lang=en}} To [[destroy]], or [[level]] to the ground. {{defdate|attested since around 1350 to 1470}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''1542''', [[w:Edward Hall|Edward Hall]], ''The Union of the Noble and Illustre Famelies of Lancastre and York'':
#*: The kynge of Scottes planted his siege before the castell of Norham, and sore '''abated''' the walls.

